			author_association: "NONE",
			active_lock_reason: null,
			body: "### Description\r\n\r\nThe semantic token docs say:\r\n> The condition can be one of chakra pseudo selectors or a _custom CSS selector_\r\n\r\n Prior to v2.6.0, adding a custom selector worked great, e.g.\r\n```\r\ntextBody: {\r\n  default: 'gray.800',\r\n  _dark: 'whiteAlpha.900',\r\n  ['.myClass']: 'red',\r\n}\r\n```\r\nBut with the latest version, any kind of custom selector breaks semantic tokens completely. The css resolves to the string \"textBody\" instead of the token value. Is there some other way we're supposed to define custom selectors? This is a big issue for us as we are using custom selectors to add high contrast mode.\r\n\r\n### Link to Reproduction\r\n\r\nhttps://codesandbox.io/s/optimistic-mendeleev-q7mg7v?file=/src/index.tsx\r\n\r\n### Steps to reproduce\r\n\r\n1. Observe that semantic tokens with a custom selector are not working with the latest Chakra version\r\n2. Change `@chakra-ui/react` version to 2.5.0 in package.json and observe that the selectors are now working as expected.\r\n\r\n### Chakra UI Version\r\n\r\n2.7.0\r\n\r\n### Browser\r\n\r\n_No response_\r\n\r\n### Operating System\r\n\r\n- [X] macOS\r\n- [ ] Windows\r\n- [ ] Linux\r\n\r\n### Additional Information\r\n\r\n_No response_",
