			body: "### Description\r\n\r\nThe components which tie their `backgroundColor` into a `status` prop (e.g. Alert and Toast's `status='success' | 'error' | 'info'` etc.) each appear to use a hard-coded mapping. It would be great if we could tie these to custom colors within the theme (in a similar manner to what can be done with `variants`).\r\n\r\n### Problem Statement/Justification\r\n\r\nAllowing the semantic color values to be altered in the theme for each of these components would more easily allow themes to be created which support users with varied forms of color-blindness reading the meaning communicated by the background color.\r\n\r\n### Proposed Solution or API\r\n\r\n```\r\nimport { extendTheme, defineStyleConfig } from '@chakra-ui/react'\r\n\r\n// Default theme for trichromatic (typical) users\r\nconst defaultTheme = extendTheme({\r\n  components: {\r\n    Alert: defineStyleConfig({\r\n      status: {\r\n        success: {\r\n          backgroundColor: 'green.400'\r\n        }\r\n      }\r\n    }),\r\n  },\r\n})\r\n\r\n// Theme for deuteranopic (green-blind) users\r\nconst DeuteranopiaTheme = extendTheme({\r\n  components: {\r\n    Alert: defineStyleConfig({\r\n      status: {\r\n        success: {\r\n          backgroundColor: 'yellow.400'\r\n        }\r\n      }\r\n    }),\r\n  },\r\n})\r\n```\r\n### Alternatives\r\n\r\nAt the moment we're using custom baked components which look similar to Chakra's Alert/Toast, but which use a set of semantic color tokens defined in our theme.\r\n\r\n### Additional Information\r\n\r\n_No response_",
